Blue Plate is a great combination of simple, fresh, comfort food and reasonable prices. It's accessible and friendly. The food can be a little hit or miss. I've been twice recently. Last time I had the squid with lemon and parsley. The squid is very fresh, but the acid on the plate is somewhat overwhelming and astringent, it has that "over-reduced lemon juice" effect. I had the tuna and my friend had the meatloaf -- both are basically perfect comfort food dishes and lovely all around. This time I had the gnocchi with braised rabbit sugo to start and my partner had the lamb with romesco. The gnocchi is great, light, not too filling, with a nice, moist pulled rabbit, but a bit of harsh, undercooked garlic stands out. No biggie, it's still delicious. The lamb is cooked properly, rested, and seasoned right. The romesco is tasty but a bit heavy on the almonds. The tabouleh is perfect. The "pork porterhouse" is a definite miss. The pork is wayyyy too salty (and peppery), and it's a bit overdone. The panzanella isn't really a salad, it's just really big chunks of old bread. Not my thing. The "stone fruit" on the plate is amazingly sweet and fresh. There's random bits of overcooked bacon lardons, mostly dry meat without any fat. Lots of random, odd, unevenly cut aromatics. The plate is a mess. If the pork weren't blow-you-away-salty, I'd say the flavors were still quite good, but it's hard to finish. The fried chicken, on the other hand -- definite hit. It's perfect southern-style chicken, great crumb on the crust, tender, and the buttermilk dressing is delicious. There's a watermelon salad with the freshest tomatoes, basil, and some olives, seasoned well and put together nicely. Having said all that, for the price, the friendly atmosphere, and the generally good food -- with some real execution problems sometimes -- it's still worthwhile. More of a 3.5 to me overall but, you know, I think places like this deserve to thrive. Give it a shot.

Very cute, funky decor, interesting wall art, but the lighting was a little low for my taste. + Fresh-from-the-oven foccacia - Our red wine was served cold. I had to put my glass by one of the candles on the table, which didn't actually do anything to warm it up. + Farro and cara cara orange salad w/ grilled puntarella and toasted hazelnuts - YUM. Delicious grains, smoky bitter greens, weird citrus (a cross between an orange and ruby red grapefruit), perfectly balanced flavors. ++Macaroni and drunken spanish goat cheese - Good lord. Amazing comfort food. Seriously some of the best mac'n'cheese out there. + Wild nettle gnocchi w/ black trumpet mushrooms, sweet onions and bellwether ricotta. The boy ordered this. He seemed quite pleased with it. I had a little bite, and the gnocchi were definitely super light and nicely textured. ++/- Hill farm pork porterhouse w/ green garlic spoon bread, belgian endive and tomato tasso mustard. This was very good. The only problem was that I thought I had ordered a porterhouse STEAK. As in cow. It arrived, looking delicious, and I tore into it. It was a little more cooked than I like my beef. It was also paler. It was hard to really see the color in the aforementioned dim lighting, so I held a chunk of meat up to one of the candles. Still hard to really tell. At some point one of the waitstaff noticed my boyfriend holding up his cellphone to the meat in an attempt to shed further light, and came over to the table. I though I had ordered a porterhouse steak, right? Happens all the time. I thanked her and went back to chowing down. The pork was delicious. As were the spoon bread (tasty, moist, crumbly) and the endive. +Warm chocolate baby cake in cold foamy sauce. This dessert has a ridiculous, unappetizing name, but was actually one of the best molten chocolate cakes ever. The molten chocolate cake is a little overdone these days, but perfect for a haute-comfort food menu. And this particular iteration of the populate dessert was dead-on delicious. I'm not gonna lie, it kinda tasted like great sex feels. +Guinness ginger cake. A dark dense ginger bread with some sort of tasty icecream. The boy got this, and loved it.

    8/29/2010

    Blue Plate is a great combination of simple, fresh, comfort food and reasonable prices.  It's accessible and friendly.  

    The food can be a little hit or miss.  I've been twice recently.  Last time I had the squid with lemon and parsley.  The squid is very fresh, but the acid on the plate is somewhat overwhelming and astringent, it has that "over-reduced lemon juice" effect.  I had the tuna and my friend had the meatloaf -- both are basically perfect comfort food dishes and lovely all around.

    This time I had the gnocchi with braised rabbit sugo to start and my partner had the lamb with romesco.  The gnocchi is great, light, not too filling, with a nice, moist pulled rabbit, but a bit of harsh, undercooked garlic stands out.  No biggie, it's still delicious.  The lamb is cooked properly, rested, and seasoned right.  The romesco is tasty but a bit heavy on the almonds.  The tabouleh is perfect.

    The "pork porterhouse" is a definite miss.  The pork is wayyyy too salty (and peppery), and it's a bit overdone.  The panzanella isn't really a salad, it's just really big chunks of old bread.  Not my thing.  The "stone fruit" on the plate is amazingly sweet and fresh.  There's random bits of overcooked bacon lardons, mostly dry meat without any fat.  Lots of random, odd, unevenly cut aromatics.  The plate is a mess.  If the pork weren't blow-you-away-salty, I'd say the flavors were still quite good, but it's hard to finish.

    The fried chicken, on the other hand -- definite hit.  It's perfect southern-style chicken, great crumb on the crust, tender, and the buttermilk dressing is delicious.  There's a watermelon salad with the freshest tomatoes, basil, and some olives, seasoned well and put together nicely.  

    Having said all that, for the price, the friendly atmosphere, and the generally good food -- with some real execution problems sometimes -- it's still worthwhile.  More of a 3.5 to me overall but, you know, I think places like this deserve to thrive.  Give it a shot.

    Very cute, funky decor, interesting wall art, but the lighting was a little low for my taste.

    + Fresh-from-the-oven foccacia

    - Our red wine was served cold.  I had to put my glass by one of the candles on the table, which didn't actually do anything to warm it up.

    + Farro and cara cara orange salad w/ grilled puntarella and toasted hazelnuts - YUM.  Delicious grains, smoky bitter greens, weird citrus (a cross between an orange and ruby red grapefruit), perfectly balanced flavors.

    ++Macaroni and drunken spanish goat cheese - Good lord.  Amazing comfort food.  Seriously some of the best mac'n'cheese out there.

    + Wild nettle gnocchi w/ black trumpet mushrooms, sweet onions and bellwether ricotta.  The boy ordered this.  He seemed quite pleased with it.  I had a little bite, and the gnocchi were definitely super light and nicely textured.

    ++/- Hill farm pork porterhouse w/ green garlic spoon bread, belgian endive and tomato tasso mustard.  This was very good.  The only problem was that I thought I had ordered a porterhouse STEAK.  As in cow.  It arrived, looking delicious, and I tore into it.  It was a little more cooked than I like my beef.  It was also paler.  It was hard to really see the color in the aforementioned dim lighting, so I held a chunk of meat up to one of the candles.  Still hard to really tell.  At some point one of the waitstaff noticed my boyfriend holding up his cellphone to the meat in an attempt to shed further light, and came over to the table.  I though I had ordered a porterhouse steak, right?  Happens all the time.  I thanked her and went back to chowing down.  The pork was delicious.  As were the spoon bread (tasty, moist, crumbly) and the endive.  

    +Warm chocolate baby cake in cold foamy sauce.  This dessert has a ridiculous, unappetizing name, but was actually one of the best molten chocolate cakes ever.  The molten chocolate cake is a little overdone these days, but perfect for a haute-comfort food menu.  And this particular iteration of the populate dessert was dead-on delicious.  I'm not gonna lie, it kinda tasted like great sex feels.

    +Guinness ginger cake.  A dark dense ginger bread with some sort of tasty icecream.  The boy got this, and loved it.

  • Sue Z.

    11/3/2006

    The last time I was here I complimented the waitress on a blueberry cheesecakey thingy dessert and she was so cute, like a little kid -- so flattered and excited because she had apparently made the dessert herself.  That's what's I like about the place -- no pretentiousness, no chi-chi foodie attitude.  The staff cares about the quality of what they create, and it's really as simple as that.
    And what they create is sophisticated, original and absolutely delicious.  There's a small list of entrees, but I definitely recommend getting a series of small plates for variety and sharing.  Everything is great, and some dishes even better.
